# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] On June 1, 2016, two men were killed in a murder-suicide at a School of Engineering building on the campus of University of California, Los Angeles (UCLA).
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] The gunman was identified as Mainak Sarkar, an Indian-born 38-year-old former UCLA Ph.D student.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] The victim was William Scott Klug, a professor who was Sarkar's thesis advisor while Sarkar was a student at UCLA.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] A woman, later identified as Sarkar's estranged wife, was found dead in Minnesota during the subsequent investigation into the shooting, and is suspected to have been killed by Sarkar several days before the UCLA shooting.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] The shooting occurred at a fourth-floor office in Engineering IV, a building that is part of the UCLA Henry Samueli School of Engineering and Applied Science.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Immediately after the shooting, Christopher Lynch, an aerospace and mechanical engineering professor who heard the gunshots, went to Klug's office and held the door shut, after which he heard another shot and then silence.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Another professor said she heard someone fall after the last shot.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Lynch later said that he did not feel the gunman try to open it but suspected the gunman heard yells for the hallway to be cleared out and that police were called in.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Lynch was credited for potentially saving lives during the shooting.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] A campus-wide alert to avoid the area was issued via UCLA's BruinAlert system at 9:49 a.m.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] PDT, and Los Angeles Police Department (LAPD) officers were summoned to the building shortly before 10:00 a.m.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] When officers responded at Engineering IV and met Lynch, he gave them his office key so they could check rooms, and then left with another professor to check on students who locked themselves in the laboratories on the lower floor.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Two handguns and a suicide note were found near the two bodies.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Shortly after the shooting, police sources told the *Los Angeles Times* that from the appearance of the bodies, a student may have killed a professor.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] At least three shots were fired in the shooting.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Based on initial reports of the shooting, authorities mistook it for an attempted mass shooting, prompting a massive police response.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] School officials put the campus on lockdown as hundreds of UCLA and LAPD officers, including SWAT officers, and officers of other agencies searched the area.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] A nearby hospital and three elementary schools were also put on lockdown.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] When the lockdown was lifted just after noon (PDT), classes at UCLA were canceled for the day.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] An apartment traced to the gunman was searched by police, and a description of his vehicle, which had not been located, was released.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] While the school was in lockdown, people at many locations found it difficult to shelter in place, as few of the doors had locks.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] As a result, some students resorted to creative mechanisms to keep the doors closed.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Scott Waugh, the school's executive vice-chancellor and provost, said the university will review its active-shooter protocols.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] The issue was previously brought up during deadly mass shootings at Virginia Tech and Sandy Hook Elementary School, where students and teachers also had to improvise to keep the doors to classrooms closed.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Although some schools across the country installed locks to doors, a more widespread adoption of this security measure was hindered by "the cost to retrofit doors and local fire codes that require doors to open in one motion during emergencies", according to experts.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Some schools and universities disagreed about the importance of door locks during active-shooter situations; the University of Colorado stated that it wanted students and teachers to rely on training instead.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] President Barack Obama was briefed about the shooting aboard Air Force One, according to White House Press Secretary Josh Earnest.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] On June 3, two days after the shooting, the gunman's car was discovered by a bicyclist, parked in a residential area in Culver City, California, located about six miles southeast of the UCLA campus.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] It contained multiple containers of gasoline and an additional handgun.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Police theorized that the containers were used to refuel the car during the gunman's drive from Minnesota to Los Angeles.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] They also theorized that the gunman parked in Culver City, where he had lived at one time, and took a bus that he regularly used to get to UCLA during his attendance there.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] On June 8, a week after the shooting, UCLA announced the launch of a task force that would review the university's response to the incident, as well as a security analysis of the campus.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] William Scott Klug (June 19, 1976 – June 1, 2016) was identified as the victim in the shooting at UCLA.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] He was a professor of mechanical and aerospace engineering.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] He was married and had two children at the time of his death.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] He was described by students as humble and easily approachable.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Colleagues said he had a strong Christian faith.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Klug received an undergraduate degree at Westmont College, a Christian liberal arts college, in 1998, and master's degree and Ph.D. degrees at UCLA and the California Institute of Technology, respectively.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Klug joined the UCLA faculty in 2003, and headed the Klug Research Group, a research group studying the field of biomechanics, specifically "theoretical and computational biomechanics", of which Sarkar was a member while a doctoral student.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Ashley Erin Hasti, Sarkar's estranged wife at the time of her murder, was found dead at her Brooklyn Park, Minnesota home.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Police found a broken window at the home, which they believe Sarkar used to break into the house.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Hasti was found the day following the shooting at UCLA after police in Los Angeles notified police in Minnesota of a note Sarkar left in his car asking authorities to check on his cat left at his home in St.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Hasti graduated from the University of Minnesota in 2008 with a bachelor's degree in Asian languages and literature.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] She completed a post-baccalaureate pre-med program at Scripps College in Claremont, California, from 2009 to 2010.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] During that time, she met Sarkar, and married him in 2011.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] At the time of her death, Hasti was a medical student at the University of Minnesota Medical School, where she had been enrolled since 2012.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] A native of Minneapolis–Saint Paul, Hasti attended North Hennepin Community College from 2003 to 2006 on a part-time basis, and also took classes there from 2011 to 2012.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] From 2011 to 2012, Hasti worked as a tutor at the community college.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Mainak Sarkar, a former Ph.D student of Klug's, was identified as the gunman on the day after the shooting.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Sarkar was born and raised in Durgapur, a city in the state of West Bengal, India.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Michael's School, a local co-education, English-medium school.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] A schoolteacher working there described Sarkar as "an ordinary boy.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Never causing any trouble to anyone." The teacher also said that Sarkar left the school to attend the nearby Durgapur Bidhan Chandra Institute.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] From 2000 to 2001, he worked for eighteen months as a software developer at Infosys in Bangalore.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] According to sources and his now-deactivated LinkedIn profile, Sarkar graduated from the Indian Institute of Technology Kharagpur in West Bengal, India, in 2000 with an undergraduate degree in aerospace engineering.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] He then traveled to the U.S. in 2001 on a student visa to pursue graduate studies.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] He first attended Stanford University from 2003 to 2005, graduating with a master's degree in aeronautical and astronautical engineering.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Sarkar then attended UCLA's engineering school from the fall of 2007 to the summer of 2013, graduating with a Ph.D. degree in solid mechanics.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Professors at UCLA described him as a "quiet and reserved" man who would not greet them whenever he passed by, and stated that he left "little impression" in their classes.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Sarkar became a permanent U.S. resident in May 2014.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] He lived in Culver City while attending UCLA, but sometime after graduating from the university, he moved to Minnesota.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] At some point after his relocation to the U.S., Sarkar briefly worked as a research assistant at the University of Texas at Arlington and as a software developer.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] After graduating from UCLA, he had been employed remotely as an engineering analyst for a rubber company in Ohio.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] In August 2014, he left his job, according to a former coworker.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Sarkar maintained a personal blog called "*thelongdarktunnel*", which has since been deleted.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] For months, he had been making hostile comments about Klug on social media, according to *The Los Angeles Times*.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] At one point, he called Klug a "very sick person" and accused him of stealing his computer code and giving it to another student.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] According to a source familiar with Sarkar and Klug's relationship, Sarkar had struggled with mental health problems such as depression, which compromised his work at UCLA.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Sarkar was linked to another murder in Brooklyn Park, Minnesota; this victim, a woman later identified as Ashley Hasti, was found shot to death in her residence.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Sarkar met and dated Hasti while both were living in California.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] According to the Hennepin County, Minnesota Clerk's Office, Sarkar and Hasti married on July 14, 2011, but at the time of the murder, they were known to have been living separately for some time.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Hasti's grandmother described Sarkar as being polite and reserved, but unable to handle Hasti teasing him.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Police believe Hasti had been dead for "maybe a couple of days" when the shooting at UCLA occurred.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Sarkar is believed to have gained entry into Hasti's home by breaking a window.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Police found a "kill list" at Sarkar's home in Saint Paul, Minnesota, which named Hasti and Klug as well as another UCLA professor who remains unidentified but is stated to be "alright" by a police official.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] This professor, who had been aware of Sarkar's issues with him, was later confirmed to have been off campus at the time of the shooting.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] After killing Hasti, Sarkar is believed by police to have equipped himself with two legally-purchased handguns, along with several rounds of ammunition and magazines, and driven from his home to Los Angeles to commit Klug's murder.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] A police official said of his weaponry, "He was certainly prepared to engage multiple victims".
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Ballistic tests indicated Klug and Hasti were both killed by the same handgun.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] A search of Sarkar's Minnesota apartment recovered more ammunition and a ballistic vest, alongside other items.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] Klug was memorialized in a tweet posted by California Lieutenant Governor Gavin Newsom, who called him an "empathetic, brilliant teacher".
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] On the day after the shooting, UCLA hosted a candlelight vigil, attended by hundreds, including the Mayor of Los Angeles, Eric Garcetti.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2016-ucla-shooting] UCLA established a support fund for Klug's family on June 7.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] On April 25, 2024, a student protest began at the University of California, Los Angeles (UCLA) to protest the administration's investments in Israel.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] The occupation, self-titled as the 'Palestine Solidarity Encampment', was a part of pro-Palestine protests on university campuses campaigning for divestment from Israel.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] The encampment was attacked multiple times by counter protestors, leading to clashes.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] On May 2, the Los Angeles Police Department (LAPD) raided and dismantled the encampment, arresting the protestors and ending the occupation.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] On April 17, pro-Palestinian protestors at Columbia University began an occupation protest on its campus to protest Columbia's investments in Israel amid the Gaza war.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] The protest, as well as its forced dismantling (when university president Minouche Shafik authorized the New York City Police Department to storm the campus and conduct mass arrests) sparked a series of nationwide protests and encampments for divestment.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Protesters have alleged that UCLA invests in organizations that do business either in, or with, Israel.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] The protestors gave BlackRock as an example of such a company that does business in Israel which they believe is part of UCLA's investment portfolio.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Closeup of graffiti and posters at Royce Hall.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] On April 25, students and faculty set up the encampment.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] IfNotNow was also present at the protests.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] The group posted online a list of demands for the administration, which includes divestment from Israel, calling for a ceasefire, and an academic boycott of Israel.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Members of pro-Israel groups included the Israeli American Council and United Jewish Coalition and other protestors in support of Israel surrounded the encampment.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Some minor skirmishes between protestors were reported.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] On April 26, the administration released a statement saying that it prioritized the safety of students and minimizing disruption, but also that it supported free expression on campus and was therefore not requesting law enforcement at that time.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] UCLA police patrolled the perimeter of the encampment.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Some Israeli and Jewish students said they felt uncomfortable.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Pro-Palestinian protestors requested UCLA to not send in police.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] On April 27, pro-Israel counter-protestors raised more than $50,000 in three hours on GoFundMe to fund a screen and loudspeaker.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Jessica Seinfeld, the wife of American comedian Jerry Seinfeld also posted on her social media account on Instagram that she had donated $5,000 to the counter-protestors.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] On April 28, the administration created a physical barrier to separate dueling protestors.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Later in the day, demonstrators broke through and a confrontation ensued.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] It was unclear what side broke through the barrier, and the administration condemned the violence.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Pro-Palestinian demonstrators also clashed with police.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Members of the Harriet Tubman Center for Social Justice held a solidarity demonstration with the pro-Palestinian protestors.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] On April 29, faculty organized a walkout in solidarity with the protestors.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Pro-Palestinian protestors set up metal barricades and appointed guards to block access to counter-protestors and media.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Counter-protestors shouted through microphones and played loud music in front of the encampment early in the day.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Later, a group of around 60 counter-protestors tried to breach the encampment, which led to heavy clashes.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Security and UC officers with riot gear briefly intervened to separate the protestors.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] During clashes, counter-protestors released mice at the encampment.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] In response to the attack, the Council on American–Islamic Relations called on UCLA administration to investigate it as a hate crime.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] A brief altercation between campus security and a disabled man occurred when the man tried to walk through a pathway blocked by the protest.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] The man said he was aware of the demonstrations, but didn't know that major pathways were blocked.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Video of a female Jewish student's bleeding head went viral.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] The student was admitted to the ER and is reported to be in stable condition.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] The victim identified herself as Elinor Hess and claimed that she was shoved down when she reached to grab her flag, which fell down, and was kicked and pulled by the hair before she lost consciousness.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] In an email to students, UCLA announced the extended closure of Powell Library and Royce Hall from 5:00 pm Tuesday, April 30.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] The facilities are planned to reopen Monday, May 6.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] On May 1, around 10:50 PM, a pro-Israeli group attacked the pro-Palestinian protesters' camp for nearly four hours, attempting to breach the barricades surrounding the encampment.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] The attackers, reported to have come from outside campus, carried Israeli flags and assaulted students with sticks, stones, poles, metal fencing, and pepper spray.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] They played loud audio of a child crying, threw wood and a metal barrier into the camp, and threw at least six fireworks into the encampment, including one directly at a group of protesters carrying injured people.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] A video investigation suggested pro-Palestinian protesters did not initiate any confrontation but acted in defense.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] The counter-protesters called for a "Second Nakba", referring to the ethnic cleansing of Palestinians in 1948, and played the Israeli national anthem and Harbu Darbu on loudspeakers during the attack.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] According to *The Guardian*, counter-protesters included several far-right activists involved in anti-LGBTQ+ and anti-vaccine campaigning.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Security personnel hired by UCLA refused to intervene and stood aside during the attack.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] LAPD officers arrived by 1:45 AM but waited at least an hour before intervening.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] None of the counter-protesters were known to have been arrested by May 3, though UCLA was investigating the attackers with help from LAPD and FBI by May 7.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Witnesses said the LAPD intervened after nearly four hours of attacks by the pro-Israel counter-demonstrators.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] One counter-protester said, "We were all waiting for the LAPD to show up and they never did".
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Both the LAPD and the university's hired security faced criticism for not protecting the encamped students.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Fifteen people were reported injured, including one who was hospitalized.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Student journalists for the *Daily Bruin* described being targeted by the counter-protesters and punched, kicked, and beaten.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] On May 15, CNN identified a number of the violent counter-protesters, but UCLA police refused to comment on whether they would press charges.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] A report found one counter-protest group raised funds through GoFundMe, with Jessica Seinfeld and Bill Ackman donating $5,000 and $10,000, respectively.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] In the evening, law enforcement in riot gear issued a dispersal order to over a thousand people who had gathered in support of the encampment, stating anyone who refused to leave could face arrest.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Following the previous night's dispersal order, an estimated 200 to 400 students remained on campus.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] At around 1:30 a.m. on May 2, LAPD officers broke into the encampment but were forced to retreat after they were outnumbered.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] After an hour, officers of the California Highway Patrol equipped in riot gear arrived at the campus to confront the protesters.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Police reportedly fired a stun grenade, surrounded the encampment from all four sides, and began tearing down its walls, arresting 210 protestors for failure to disperse, reportedly including at least one professor.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Police were seen firing rubber bullets at the student protestors and methodically dismantling the encampment, that was cleared by the morning.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] On the morning of Monday, May 6, UCPD arrested 44 pro-Palestine protestors, 35 of whom were students, in Parking Lot 2.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Four of those arrested were previously arrested in the May 2 raid on the encampment.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] In parallel, approximately 50 protestors staged a sit-in protest at Moore Hall.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] UCPD responded by closing the building, after which the protestors moved to Dodd Hall.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] The protestors then moved to Bruin Plaza to continue their protest.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] A person claiming to speak for behalf of the local chapter of the Students for Justice in Palestine group told the Daily Bruin that the group would not allow for business as usual to continue at the university, and they wanted to "disrupt the university’s finances".
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] On the same day, UAW Local 4811, the chapter representing over 48,000 University of California workers under the United Auto Workers union, issued an authorization to vote for a strike, with the vote scheduled to take place May 13 thru 15.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] On the morning of May 23, the day that chancellor Block testified in front of the House Education Committee, a small group of protesters set up a small encampment on the patio of Kerckhoff Hall.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] The number of protesters eventually reached several hundreds within a few hours.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] In the early afternoon, the UCPD issued a dispersal order and the protestors voluntarily left, marching towards the administration building, Murphy Hall, where they were joined by several hundred other protestors.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] With security denying access to the protestors to Murphy Hall, the protestors crossed the street to Dodd Hall.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Some protestors were able to enter Dodd Hall, where they barricaded themselves, with the rest of the protestors blocking access to the building.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Some counter-protestors attempted to enter Dodd Hall, but were denied entry by the protestors.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] In the late afternoon, the protestors decided to leave voluntarily just prior to the police entering the building through a back entrance.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] No arrests were made, and there were no reports of injuries.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Protesters set up an encampment at Dickson Plaza and dyed a nearby fountain red.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Protesters had attempted to set up an encampment at Janns Steps.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] When they were dispersed by police, they attempted to set up an encampment at Kerckhoff patio.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] After the police warned them again, they attempted to set up at Dodd Hall and the School of Law where police shot rubber bullets at them.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] On October 21, 2024 local chapters of Jewish Voice for Peace and Students for Justice in Palestine erected a Sukkah at Dickson Court to protest the Gaza war.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Organizers had intended to keep the sukkah up for 7 days, commensurate with the Jewish holiday of Sukkot lasting 7 days.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Some protestors also set up tents around the sukkah.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] By nightfall, when the UCPD dispersed the protest, the encampment grew to 40 protestors with about 30 counter-protestors heckling the protestors.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] One person was arrested for failure to dispurse.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Following the attack on the encampment by Pro-Israel counter-protestors on May 1, California governor Gavin Newsom stated, "The limited and delayed campus law enforcement response at UCLA last night was unacceptable — and it demands answers".
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Los Angeles Mayor Karen Bass released a statement saying police had responded to a request from UCLA administration, later describing the violence as "abhorrent".
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Following the police storming of the encampment, U.S. president Joe Biden said he supported law enforcement, stating, "We’re a civil society and order must prevail".
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] In late-May 2024, the UCLA chief of police was removed from his post.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Police Commission found that a lack of communication between UCLA, the LAPD, and the California Highway Patrol had contributed to the failed response to the April 30 attack on campus.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] In a statement, the protesters said, "The life-threatening assault we face tonight is nothing less than a horrifying, despicable act of terror.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Law enforcement simply stood at the edge of the lawn and refused to budge as we screamed for their help." One student speaking to CNN stated, "The police the university had hired, the private security guards, stared and watched as this happened".
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Another student speaking to *The Guardian* said after being twice hit over the head, he "was left with stitches on his forehead and 14 staples in the back of his head".
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] The editorial board for the student newspaper, The Daily Bruin, released an op-ed condemning the university for failing to protect students and the encampment.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] UCLA Chancellor Gene Block released a statement denouncing the May 1 conflict, stating "this attack on our students, faculty and community members was utterly unacceptable", describing the counter-protesters who attacked the encampment as "instigators".
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Faculty condemned the lack of a response to the counter-protestors, including Ananya Roy, who said, "The word is out they can do this repeatedly and get away with it.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] A UCLA professor of Jewish history, David N.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Myers, stated that "some of the attackers appeared to be carrying Israeli flags and other pro-Israel symbols", in reference to the violence.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] The administration released an email statement saying that they were "sickened" by the violence and that they called law enforcement to help control the situation.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] UCLA cancelled classes and alerted students that there would be "law enforcement presence stationed throughout campus." Remote instruction was announced for Thursday and Friday classes.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Faculty members of the History Department released a statement condemning the violent attacks on the students and called for the UCLA Chancellor as well as the UC President to be held accountable for their inaction.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] The Faculty for Justice in Palestine chapter at UCLA called for a labor strike on May 2, 2024.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] UAW Local 4811, the union representing over 48,000 academic workers at the 11 UC campuses announced that it would hold a strike authorization vote within a week in response to the violence against students at UCLA.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] The UCLA branch of Hillel International, an organization that supports Jewish life and Israel on student campuses released an unsigned statement condemning the violent attack on all students and requesting off-campus Jewish community to stay away from on-campus protests.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] On May 16, the UCLA Faculty's Academic Senate voted on a no confidence vote and resolution to censure Chancellor Block over his handling of the violence committed by counterprotesters against the encampment on April 30.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Both resolutions were defeated with 43% votes in favor of no confidence, and 50% in favor of censure.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] On May 22, the UCLA Police Chief John Thomas, who was under intense criticism for the slow response to the violence against the encampment on April 30, was removed and replaced while the University studies its security procedures.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] In March 2025, UCLA banned the Students for Justice in Palestine student organization.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] On May 20 the United Auto Workers Local 4811 representing teaching assistants and research assistants throughout the University of California launched a rotating strike in which each day a different campus would strike.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] On May 28 the rotating strike arrived at UCLA.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] On May 24, the UCLA Police Department arrested an 18-year old Beverly Hills High School student named Edan On on suspicion of assault with a deadly weapon.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Police said that On was recorded attacking the pro-Palestinian encampment at UCLA during the pro-Israel counter-protest.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] On was booked on a felony charge and held on a $30,000 bail.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] CNN had identified On along with other counter-protesters through a review of hundreds of hours of videos, social media posts and interviews.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] The UCLA Police Department also conducted their own investigation which included interviewing victims and witnesses and reviewing security camera footage and social media videos from members of the public and media.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] On June 21, the office of the Los Angeles County District Attorney declined to press felony charges against Edan On, and referred the case to the Los Angeles City Attorney for possible misdemeanor charges.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] In declining to file felony charges, the district attorney cited lack of evidence that On's conduct directly resulted in any injuries, nor any evidence of conspiracy.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] City Attorney Hydee Feldstein Soto announced that criminal charges would be filed against Edan On and Matthew Katz.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] No other criminal charges were filed as a result of the protests.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] On 23 May 2024, UCLA Chancellor Gene Block testified at the House Education Committee.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Representative Ilhan Omar stated, "You, the UCLA leadership and law enforcement stood by for hours as the mob of agitators gathered near the encampment with the clear intention to cause violence".
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] In an op-ed in *The Guardian*, activist Judith Levine criticized U.S. media coverage of the counter-protester attack, particularly outlets' refraining from assigning blame and for using the passive voice.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] On May 1, the day after the counter-protester violence, Dr.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Phil filmed segments for his syndicated talk show at the encampment.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] On May 16, CNN published an investigative piece where they attempted to identify those that participated in the attack on the encampment, based on posted social media, footage, and interviews.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Several individuals were identified by name in the piece, including Edan On, Malachi Marlan-Librett, and Tom Bibiyan.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] However, she later denied that her son had been at the encampment.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] On May 23, the UCLA Police Department arrested Edan On on suspicion of assault with a deadly weapon, a felony charge.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] On was “was seen on video assaulting encampment occupants with a wooden pole” according to a statement released to CNN.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] On August 13, Judge Mark Scarsi issued a preliminary injunction in favor of the Jewish students, saying that the university cannot allow protestors to violate the civil rights of Jewish students by blocking them from accessing certain areas within the campus for holding faith-based views.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Judge Scarsi said that it was "unimaginable" and "abhorrent" for Jewish students to be unable to use parts of the university campus, including Powell Library, "because they refused to denounce their faith".
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] The ruling effectively requires the university to either ensure that Jewish students are "fully and equally" able to participate in all parts of the school that are ordinarily open to students, or to close those programs and places for all students.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] A separate lawsuit was also filed in June by a student who by that time had already graduated.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] In his lawsuit against UCLA, the student, Milagro Jones, blamed the university for an assault he suffered by the protestors at the encampment.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Jones faulted UCLA for not acting soon enough to shut down the encampment.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/2024-university-of-california-los-angeles-pro-palestinian-campus-occupation] Although Jones is not Jewish, he was nonetheless accused by the protestors of being a Zionist.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aaron-copland-school-of-music] The **Aaron Copland School of Music** is one of the oldest departments at Queens College at the City University of New York, founded when the College opened in 1937.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aaron-copland-school-of-music] The department's curriculum was originally established by Edwin Stringham, and a later emphasis on the analytical system of Heinrich Schenker was initiated by Saul Novack.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aaron-copland-school-of-music] Some of the students who enrolled in early classes of the college later became faculty members of the department.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aaron-copland-school-of-music] This included Sol Berkowitz, Gabriel Fontrier, Leo Kraft.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aaron-copland-school-of-music] Joseph Machlis, developed the teaching of music appreciation to a high art, and wrote the most successful series of music appreciation textbooks in history.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Aboriginal people began using dugout canoes from around 1640 in coastal regions of northern Australia.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] They were brought by Buginese fishers of sea cucumbers, known as trepangers, from Makassar in South Sulawesi.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] In Arnhem Land, dugout canoes used by the local Yolngu people are called *lipalipa* or *lippa-lippa*.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Aboriginal canoes were constructed much more easily than previous types of vessels, such as bark canoes.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] This ease of construction played a significant role in the dugout canoes’ widespread use.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] While earlier vessels required a great deal of labor and time-consuming sewing to make, dugout canoes were constructed easily and in a shorter period of time.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] First, one would have to cut down a tree and shape the exterior into an even form.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The sides of the canoe were shaped in one of two ways.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] They were either carved straight up and down or in a "u" shape, curving in towards the center of the boat.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Next, one would have to dig out the inner wood of the log to make space for the oarsmen to sit and paddle.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] In some early dugout canoes, Aboriginal people would not make the bottoms of the canoes smooth, but would instead carve "ribbing" into the vessel.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Ribbing (literally sections of wood that looked like ribs) was used to stabilize bark canoes, and though not necessary to dugout canoes, was a carryover in the transition from one canoe type to the other.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Both the chopping down of the tree and the digging out of the log were easily done with an iron-axe.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The wood used in the construction of dugout canoes was essential to its strength and durability.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Sycamores are strong and extremely durable, making them suitable for use in the construction of dugout canoes.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Both sea turtles and dugongs were essential components of the Aboriginal diet.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The transformation from bark canoes to dugout canoes greatly increased the ability of the tribal hunters to catch and kill both of these types of sea creatures due primarily to a more formidable structure.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Dugout canoes included a stronger and better platform for harpooning that greatly increased the stability of an upright hunter by providing essential footing.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] In order to capture dugongs and sea turtles, the hunters needed to maintain the utmost degree of stealth.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Perfect balance was required and the new dugout canoes gave the hunters this necessary edge.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Additionally, the shift towards using dugout canoes maximized the overall possibilities of seafarers.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Not only did increased sturdiness, speed and stability of Dugout canoes make hunting easier, but these characteristics also allowed for long-distance travel.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Whereas bark canoes had been only used for inland use or travel extremely close to the shore, Dugout canoes offered a far greater range of travel which allowed for trade outside the area of the village.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Dugout canoes were capable of traveling distances over 500 km.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] This new vessel gave the Aboriginal people the ability and opportunity to explore, trade and locate additional resources located outside the central location.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The widespread use of dugout canoes had many impacts on Aboriginal life.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The most significant were results of the Aboriginal peoples' ability to hunt larger prey.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] With the strength to transport larger prey over longer distances, dugout enabled the peoples to vastly expand their hunting grounds.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] This larger prey also enabled support of a larger group of people over a longer period of time.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] This increase in the ability to support population led to both population growth and expansion.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Torres Strait Islander people, another Indigenous Australian group of peoples (who are not Aboriginal), used a different type of boat – a double outrigger, unique to their area and probably introduced from Papuan communities and later modified.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] It was about 14 metres (46 ft) long, with two bamboo masts and sails made of pandanus-mat.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] They could sail as far as 80 kilometres (50 mi) and carry up to twelve people.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] The Afghan community in the United States was minimal until large numbers were admitted as refugees following the December 1979 Soviet invasion of Afghanistan.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Others have arrived similarly during and after the latest war in Afghanistan.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Afghan Americans reside and work all across the United States.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] The states of California, Virginia and New York historically had the largest number of Afghan Americans.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Thousands may also be found in the states of Arizona, Texas, Georgia, Colorado, Washington, Oklahoma, Nebraska, Missouri, North Carolina, Maryland and Illinois.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Afghan Americans have a long history of immigrating to the United States, as they have arrived as early as the 1860s.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] This was around the time when Afghanistan–United States relations were being established.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Wallace Fard Muhammad claimed to have been from Afghanistan.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] A World War I draft registration card for *Wallie Dodd Fard* from 1917 indicated he was living in Los Angeles, California, as an unmarried restaurant owner, and reported that he was born in Shinka, Afghanistan in 1893.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Between the 1920s and 1940s, hundreds of Afghans immigrated to the United States.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Between 1953 and early 1970, at least 230 lawfully entered the United States.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Some of them were students who had been granted scholarships to study in American universities.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] After the 1979 Soviet invasion of Afghanistan, around five million Afghan citizens were displaced.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] They were compelled to secretly migrate to (or seek refuge in) other countries.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] These Afghan refugees or asylum seekers found temporary shelter in neighboring Pakistan and Iran, and from there thousands made it to Europe, North America, Oceania, and elsewhere in the world.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Under the law, the ones born in Pakistan, Iran or India are not in any way Pakistanis, Iranians or Indians.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Their birth certificates and other legal documents confirm that they are citizens of Afghanistan.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Beginning in 1980, Afghan Americans arrived into the United States as families.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] They were admitted as refugees or asylum seekers.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] In some cases a family was represented by only one parent due to the death of the other parent.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] They began settling in the New York metropolitan area, California (mainly in the San Francisco Bay Area and the Los Angeles-Orange County area) and in other parts of the United States, where large Muslim community centers keep them bonded.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Fremont, California, is home to the largest population of Afghan Americans followed by Northern Virginia and then Queens in New York City.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Smaller Afghan American communities also exist in the states of Texas, Arizona, Oklahoma, Washington, Georgia, Michigan, Idaho, Missouri, Illinois, Pennsylvania, Florida, North Carolina, Massachusetts, Maryland, Connecticut, Colorado, Ohio, Utah, New Mexico, Oregon, Tennessee and so on.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] In the city of Chicago, the 2000 census counted 556 Afghan Americans, approximately half of them within the city.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] The first arrivals of Afghan families in the early 1980s were mainly the wealthy and from the urban and educated elite.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] They had rightfully applied for refugee status while temporarily residing in Pakistan and India, and a large number had similarly resided in Germany before their firm resettlement in the United States.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] The family reunification program brought in less affluent communities from rural Afghanistan, many of which were illiterate and maintained a more traditional village lifestyle.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Those admitted under 8 U.S.C. § 1157 and becoming green card recipients under 8 U.S.C. § 1159(a) are statutorily protected against inadmissibility, even if they are not in possession of their green cards, Afghan passports, Afghan identity cards, or any other legal document.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] In addition to that privilege or benefit, whenever one parent becomes naturalized all of his or her children statutorily become entitled to naturalization through such American parent.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] This conferral of American nationality statutorily extends to all of his or her children that are born outside of the United States.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] All such nationality claims are statutorily reviewable under the federal judiciary of the United States.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Post September 11, 2001, the Afghan American community faced discriminations.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] President Bush's plan to legalize works to help the economy came to a halt after the terror attack in 2001.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] It interrupted talk of legalizing immigrants thus leading to few admitted immigrants from 2001 to 2005.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] 406,080 immigrant visas were issued in 2001.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] 395,005 were issued in 2005 according to the Department of Homeland Security.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] A news reporter in 2001 randomly stated, without providing any references or sources, that there were 200,000 Afghan Americans.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] This wild assumption probably included Afghan Canadians.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Census Bureau, there were approximately 65,972 Afghan-Americans in 2006.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] The American Community Survey (ACS) estimated a total of 94,726 Afghan foreign-born immigrants were residing and working in the United States in 2016, which shows a 30% increase in the last ten years.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Since 2005, thousands of Afghans have been admitted to the United States under the Special Immigrant Visa (SIV) program.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Congress passed the Afghan Allies Protection Act of 2009, which was extended in 2014.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Afghans who had put their lives at risk during the US-led war in Afghanistan became eligible for SIVs.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] This program for Afghans created a legal pathway towards U.S. citizenship for the recipients and their immediate family members.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Large numbers of Afghans, including those that worked with the United States, moved to the country following the Taliban take over of Kabul in August 2021.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Of the more than 100,000 Afghan nationals who have moved to the United States since August 2021, it has accepted more than 1,600 unaccompanied children, the Department of Health and Human Services' Office of Refugee Resettlement records show.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] As many as 150,000 Afghans who assisted the United States remained in Afghanistan, including individuals who worked closely with US military forces.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Afghans who went through resettlement difficulties may experience discrimination, worsening the trauma.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Afghans still continue to flee from Afghanistan and still struggle to find refuge, most recently on July 15 Canada had closed its Special Immigration Measures Program.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Afghans who were relying on this program may face death or persecution due to being stuck in Afghanistan, especially since this program targeted former employees of the Canadian Armed Forces, the Canadian Governments and their families.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] is a traditional rice dish topped with sweet carrots, raisins, sliced almonds and served usually with lamb, beef or chicken.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] As other immigrants in the United States, Afghan Americans have gradually adopted the American way of life.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] But many of those who were born in Afghanistan still highly value Afghan culture.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] For example, they often wear at home Afghan clothes, watch Afghan shows, listen to Afghan music, eat mostly Afghan food, and enthusiastically keep up with Afghan politics.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] They also value their oral tradition of story telling.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] The stories they sometimes tell are about Mullah Nasreddin, Afghan history, myths and religions.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Afghan Americans celebrate August 19 as Afghan Independence Day, which relates to August 1919, the date when Afghanistan became fully independent after the signing of the Anglo-Afghan Treaty.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Small festivals are held in cities that have Afghan communities, usually at the parks where black, red and green colored Afghan flags are spotted around cars.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Eid and Nowruz remain popular festivals for Afghans.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] The 2021 American sitcom *United States of Al* featured American and Afghan culture.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Afghan Americans are composed of the various ethnic groups that exist in Afghanistan, which include Pashtun, Tajik, Hazara, Uzbek, Turkmen, Baloch, and a number of others.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Since 1945, Afghan Americans have been officially classified as Caucasians.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Census purposes Afghans are racially categorized as White Americans.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] In recent years the creation of a new census category called SWANA (which includes Afghan Americans) has been proposed in an effort for more accurate categorization.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] The majority of Afghan-Americans are Muslims whom follow Sunni Islam, with a sizable community of Shia Muslims.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Many Afghan Americans residing in Northern Virginia are members of the All Dulles Area Muslim Society, which has a number of local branches.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] After the September 11 attacks in 2001, a mosque run by Afghan-Americans in New York City donated blood, held a vigil for those who died inside the World Trade Center (WTC) and funded a memorial for the New York City fire fighters.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] There is a community of Afghan Jews in New York City, numbering about 200 families in 2007.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] A group of Afghan Americans in the Los Angeles area follow Christianity.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Hussain Andaryas is an Afghan Christian televangelist who belongs to the Hazara ethnic group.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Outside of the Abrahamic faiths, there exists a community of Afghan Hindus and Afghan Sikhs.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] They are mainly found in the states of New York and Maryland.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Afghan Americans have formed media outlets dedicated for its diaspora.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Examples include television channels such as Ariana Afghanistan, Payam-e-Afghan, Tuti TV, and Pamir TV.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] In the 1990s, *Afghanistan TV* broadcast on KSCI Channel 18 in Los Angeles and as well as magazines like the *Afghanistan Mirror*.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Many organizations have also been formed for Afghan youth, solidarity, women's rights and more.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Recently a new radio station has also launched named Radio Afghan Los Angeles.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] In 2020, "Afghanistan by Afghans" a TV show and podcast was started by Misaq Kazimi, showcasing the voices of Afghan artists, thinkers and cultural keepers.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] According to estimates from the Migration Policy Institute website for 2017–2021, there were 118,500 Afghan immigrants in the United States.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Many Afghan Americans own real estate in Afghanistan, which in some cases have been lawfully inherited from their earliest ancestors for generations upon generations.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Afghan Americans who arrived before the 21st century are mostly found residing near other middle class Americans.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Some may be found living in the upper middle class neighborhoods and earning high salaries.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Because the majority of Afghan Americans were originally admitted as refugees under 8 U.S.C. § 1157, the government provided various forms of assistance (welfare) and selected their city of residence.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Some decided to move to other cities that had larger Afghan communities but most remained in the cities where they first arrived.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] They gradually left the government assistance programs and eventually mortgaged homes.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Their children were sent to colleges or universities.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Those who could not achieve this decided to build or franchise small businesses.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Others became real estate agents, bank employees, office workers, hotel workers, store clerks, salespersons, security guards, drivers, mechanics, waiters, etc.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Like many other immigrants in the United States, Afghan Americans often engage in the operation of small businesses.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Many operate American and Afghan restaurants as well as Afghan markets, while some have been reported in the 1990s as vendors in Manhattan where they have replaced Greek Americans in the field.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] The family incomes of Afghan Americans (specifically, those that were termed "refugees") was a median of $50,000 in 2015.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] This figure is higher than Mexican Americans, Cuban Americans and slightly higher than Hmong Americans, but lower than Vietnamese Americans.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Afghan immigrants that were admitted to the United States before 1979 were well educated.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] In contrast, current immigrants have escaped from totalitarianism, genocide, torture, persecution, mistreatment, and military conflicts.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] This group has had some trouble coping with learning the English language.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] Those who have pursued their education in America during the middle of the 20th century and traveled back to Afghanistan faced trouble attaining employment when returning to the United States since their education, often in medicine and engineering, is frequently viewed as outdated.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/afghan-americans] After the 1979 Soviet invasion, Afghanistan's education system worsened, causing many migrants in the late 20th century to place less emphasis on educational attainment.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium] Since its creation, AAPIPRC has sponsored annual conferences focused on connecting national, state and local agencies to AAPI policy and research.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium] Hosted by the National Education Association in Washington D.C., the 2012 conference focused on "Expanding the Asian American and Pacific Islander Voice in National Policy." The 2013 conference focused on the use of survey and other research methodology to inform AAPI policy.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/ote-a] The **ʻōteʻa** (usually written as *otea*) is a traditional dance and accompanying music from Tahiti characterized by a rapid hip-shaking motion to percussion accompaniment.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/ote-a] The dancers, standing in several rows, may be further choreographed to execute different figures (including tamau, varu, otamu, ami, and fa'arapu) while maintaining the hip-shaking.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/ote-a] The hip motion itself may in some choreographies be synchronized amongst multiple dancers and may be further coordinated with the accompanying percussion arrangement.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/ote-a] The dance is with music only (drums) at a fast rhythm, and no singing.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/ote-a] The drum can be one of the different types of the *tōʻere*, a lying log of wood with a longitudinal slit, which is struck by one or two sticks.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/ote-a] Additional drum types accompanying the dance may include the ng drum covered with a shark skin and struck by the hands or with sticks) played at a slower rhythm, or the smaller *faʻatētē* drum.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/ote-a] The ʻōteʻa is one of the few dances which already existed in pre-European times as a male dance.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/ote-a] (The *hura* (Tahitian vernacular for hula), a dance for women, on the other hand has disappeared, and likewise is gone the couple's dance ʻupaʻupa but which may have reemerged as the tāmūrē).
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/ote-a] Nowadays, however the ʻōteʻa can be danced by men (ʻōteʻa tāne), by women (ʻōteʻa vahine), or by both genders (ʻōteʻa ʻāmui = united ʻō.).
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/ote-a] Dancers of the ʻōteʻa make gestures reenacting daily occupations of life.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/ote-a] For the men the gestural themes can be chosen from warfare or sailing, and then they may use spears or paddles.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/ote-a] For women the gestural themes are typically closer to home or from nature: hand gestures suggesting combing their hair, or the flight of a butterfly.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/ote-a] More elaborate themes have been adopted; for example one where the dancers end up in a map of Tahiti, highlighting important places.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/ote-a] In a proper ʻōteʻa the story of the theme should pervade the whole dance.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/ote-a] The costumes are extremely elaborate, typically incorporating long plant fiber ("grass") skirts, belting with tassels that accentuate the hip-motion, may further include decorated headpieces, and may be color-coordinated across the dancers of the company.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/ote-a] The same *more* dress and the same shaking of the knees for the boys and of the hips for the girls as in all Tahitian dances (see tāmūrē) is used here too.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/ote-a] Interpretations of the **ʻōteʻa** are frequently included as part of larger Polynesian dance recitals presented at luaus and visitor-oriented live shows in the Hawaiian Islands and other Pacific-rim resorts outside Tahiti.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/ote-a] Modern drum accompaniments may include drums of European or non-Pacific construction, improvised percussion instruments of modern materials (e.g. high-density polyethylene or metallic commercial food packaging), and the use of prerecorded drum reinforcement soundtracks.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/upa-upa] The **ʼupaʼupa** (often written as **upa upa**) is a traditional dance from Tahiti.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/upa-upa] It was mentioned by European explorers, who described it as very indecent.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/upa-upa] It is not quite clear how similar the gestures at that time were with the now immensely popular tāmūrē.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/upa-upa] In both dances the performers form groups of pairs of a boy and a girl, dancing more or less in sexually oriented movements.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/upa-upa] The musical setting usually includes voice, flute, and drums.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/upa-upa] After having arrived on Tahiti in 1797, the LMS missionaries quickly intimidated the local rulers of the island and fixed themselves in a position of power.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/upa-upa] Although this enabled them to abolish such habits as infanticide, cannibalism and tribal wars, it also enabled them to introduce the idea of sin, which was unknown on Tahiti until then.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/upa-upa] The joy of dancing, so dear to the Polynesian heart, was one of the first to be axed.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/upa-upa] The famous Pōmare code of 1819 declared the ʼupaʼupa (and tattooing in the same line) to be bad and immoral habitudes, severely to be opposed.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/upa-upa] In the code of 1842 many restrictions were relaxed, but the ʼupaʼupa (the general term for dancing then) remained on the black list.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/upa-upa] In the same year the French proclaimed the protectorate.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/upa-upa] Being Catholic with some broader views on life than the Protestants, and considering that "if you cannot beat them, join them", they proclaimed in the official bulletin of 1849 that the ʼupaʼupa was still forbidden, except on public feastdays, but then still without the indecent gestures.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/upa-upa] The act of 1853, repeated in 1876 was more restrictive.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/upa-upa] In the hope that the Tahitians would spend their time on more pious occupations than dancing and drinking, a system of licenses was introduced.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/upa-upa] A license could only be obtained by a chef and only on Saturday evenings.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/upa-upa] Despite all these restrictions, dancing went on, less secret or more secret depending on the law at that moment.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/upa-upa] Nevertheless, many years of suppression had left a mark on it, and although the idea and the steps were still there, the ʼupaʼupa of the old did not really exist anymore.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/upa-upa] In the beginning of the 20th century Tahitian dances were only performed on such festivities as 14 July and saw an evolution into what they have become nowadays.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/upa-upa] Around 1900 the traditional costumes came back, and although they still looked more like mother Hubbard dresses or ponchos, at least they were made of traditional materials.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/upa-upa] Around 1920 strips of raffia were added, which soon would develop into the characteristic *more* or grass skirt (in reality made from hibiscus fibers) of Tahiti.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/upa-upa] The bare torso (for men only) became acceptable.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/upa-upa] Prizes started to be awarded to the best dancers on a festival.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/upa-upa] But it was not until 1956 that Madeleine Mouʼa organised a dance group, called the *heiva*, of which Teriʼi and Takau, daughters of the last queen of Tahiti became patrons.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/upa-upa] Finally then traditional dancing had the blessing from the establishment.
[src:asian-american-and-pacific-islander-policy-research-consortium/upa-upa] The opening of Faaʼa International Airport in 1961 and the real start of the tourist industry on Tahiti made all the dances which had come forth from the ʼupaʼupa a part of daily life once more.
